<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="120" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,756,1769,1857]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,270,1769,1793]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">Etymology</emphasis>
: The specific epithet is the present participle of the Latin verb desculpere (to chisel) and alludes to the chisel-shaped internal structure of the aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="120" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,757,1897,2081]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,288,1897,1921]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">Description:</emphasis>
Body length 
<quantity box="[447,576,1897,1921]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" metricValueMax="2.4" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="17" pageNumber="120" unit="mm" value="2.25" valueMax="2.4" valueMin="2.1">2.1–2.4 mm</quantity>
; length of forebody 0.9–1.0 mm. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation box="[540,601,1929,1953]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="6.[189,229,1981,2003]" captionTargetBox="[195,1433,232,1956]" captionTargetId="figure-94@6.[189,1436,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 1–8: Male habitusof Leptusaspp.1 – L.excisa; 2 – L.grandipennis; 3– L.auriculata; 4– L.gonggana; 5– L.emeiana; 6 – L. jizuica;" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5743066" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5743066/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
. Colouration: forebody brown to dark-brown with the humeral angles and the posterior margins of the elytra reddish-yellow; legs yellowish; antennae brown with the basal three antennomeres and antennomere XI reddish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[794,1399,233,1121]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[870,946,233,257]" captionStart="Figs 9–18" captionStartId="7.[151,191,1982,2004]" captionTargetBox="[153,1398,232,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 9–18: Male habitus (9–11) and forebody (12–18) of Leptusa spp. 9, 15 – L. habana; 10 – L. monscangi; 11 – L. pathibarana; 12 – L. excisa; 13 – L. grandipennis; 14 – L. gonggana; 16 – L. auriculata; 17 – L. jizuica; 18 – L. desculpens. Scale bars:9–16: 1.0 mm; 17–18: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5743070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5743070/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
) approximately as long as broad; punctation very coarse and dense, interstices reduced to narrow ridges. Eyes shorter than postocular region in lateral view. Antenna incrassate apically; antennomeres IV weakly transverse, V–X increasing in width and increasingly transverse, and X approximately twice as broad as long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[794,1399,233,1121]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[919,994,457,481]" captionStart="Figs 9–18" captionStartId="7.[151,191,1982,2004]" captionTargetBox="[153,1398,232,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 9–18: Male habitus (9–11) and forebody (12–18) of Leptusa spp. 9, 15 – L. habana; 10 – L. monscangi; 11 – L. pathibarana; 12 – L. excisa; 13 – L. grandipennis; 14 – L. gonggana; 16 – L. auriculata; 17 – L. jizuica; 18 – L. desculpens. Scale bars:9–16: 1.0 mm; 17–18: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5743070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5743070/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
) approximately 1.2 times as broad as long and 1.2 times as broad as head; maximal width in anterior half; posterior angles marked; punctation similar to that of head, but somewhat less coarse.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[794,1399,233,1121]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">
Elytra (
<figureCitation box="[871,945,585,609]" captionStart="Figs 9–18" captionStartId="7.[151,191,1982,2004]" captionTargetBox="[153,1398,232,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 9–18: Male habitus (9–11) and forebody (12–18) of Leptusa spp. 9, 15 – L. habana; 10 – L. monscangi; 11 – L. pathibarana; 12 – L. excisa; 13 – L. grandipennis; 14 – L. gonggana; 16 – L. auriculata; 17 – L. jizuica; 18 – L. desculpens. Scale bars:9–16: 1.0 mm; 17–18: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5743070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5743070/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
) approximately 0.8 times as long as pronotum, extensively impressed; punctation very coarse, dense and asperate. Hind wings reduced.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[794,1399,233,1121]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">Abdomen approximately as broad as elytra; tergites III–V with anterior impressions densely and coarsely punctate; punctation distinct and moderately fine, dense on anterior tergites and sparser on posterior tergites; interstices glossy, without distinct microsculpture; posterior margin of tergite VII without palisade fringe; tergites VII and VIII sexually dimorphic.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[794,1399,233,1121]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">
: tergites VII and VIII each with oblong postero-median tubercle (Fig. 63); posterior margin of sternite VIII obtusely produced in the middle (Fig. 64); median lobe of aedeagus approximately 
<quantity box="[1099,1181,1001,1025]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="120" unit="mm" value="0.3">0.3 mm</quantity>
long, shaped as in Figs 61–62; internal structures of distinctive shapes; apical lobe of paramere distinctly oblong.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[794,1399,233,1121]" box="[794,936,1097,1121]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">: unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[794,1399,1161,1313]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[794,1002,1161,1185]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">Comparative notes</emphasis>
: This species is readily distinguished from all other congeners recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[1251,1316,1193,1217]" name="China" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">China</collectingCountry>
by the distinctive internal structures of the aedeagus and additionally by the combination of small size, slender habitus, and conspicuously coarse punctation of the forebody.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="120" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="17.[794,1399,1353,1505]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[794,1156,1353,1377]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">Distribution and natural history</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2021" box="[1171,1372,1353,1377]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Leptusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="desculpens">
<emphasis box="[1171,1372,1353,1377]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">Leptusa desculpens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is currently the sole representative of the genus known from Southeast 
<collectingRegion box="[904,991,1418,1441]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
. The specimens were sifted from litter in a primary broad-leaved forest in Dawei Shan, 
<collectingRegion box="[1309,1395,1450,1473]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
, at an altitude of 
<quantity box="[965,1046,1481,1505]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" pageId="17" pageNumber="120" unit="m" value="2100.0">2100 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
